{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:34:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:34:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18667"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.12,0.48,0.1,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76718"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62210"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2530"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26414"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76718"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening breathlessness and wheeze. She has never had asthma or allergies previously. She reports general fatigue, intermittent fever, and a 4 kg weight loss over the past two months. She has also noticed numbness in her feet and a rash on her legs. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals bilateral wheeze. There are several purpuric lesions on her lower legs. Neurological examination demonstrates reduced sensation to light touch in a stocking distribution.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 112 g/L (115-165)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 15.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ENeutrophils: 8.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (2.0-7.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EEosinophils: 2.5 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.0-0.5)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets: 450 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EC-reactive protein: 85 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to reveal the underlying diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-double stranded DNA antibodies","Chest X-ray","Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies","Aspergillus precipitins","Serum IgE level"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with adult-onset asthma accompanied by constitutional symptoms, peripheral neuropathy, skin manifestations, and marked eosinophilia. These features strongly suggest eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA, formerly known as Churg-Strauss syndrome).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E (ANCA) testing is the most appropriate investigation as it can confirm the diagnosis of EGPA. Approximately 40% of EGPA patients are ANCA positive, typically with a perinuclear pattern (p-ANCA) specific for myeloperoxidase (MPO). This patient\u0027s presentation with purpura and peripheral neuropathy is particularly suggestive of ANCA-positive disease, which tends to show more vasculitic features compared to ANCA-negative disease which typically presents with more tissue eosinophilia and cardiac involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum IgE level\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in EGPA but is non-specific and can be raised in many conditions including allergic asthma, parasitic infections, and other eosinophilic disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-double stranded DNA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with systemic lupus erythematosus and would not explain this constellation of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspergillus precipitins\u003C/strong\u003E would be more relevant if allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis was suspected, which typically presents with long-standing asthma rather than new-onset disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may show pulmonary infiltrates in EGPA but is non-specific and less helpful in establishing the diagnosis compared to ANCA testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of EGPA is based on a combination of clinical features including asthma, eosinophilia, neuropathy, pulmonary infiltrates, paranasal sinus abnormalities, and histological evidence of eosinophilic vasculitis. ANCA-positive patients like this one typically present with more vasculitic manifestations including glomerulonephritis, peripheral neuropathy, and purpura. In contrast, ANCA-negative patients tend to have more cardiac involvement, fever, and lung infiltrates due to tissue eosinophilia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adult-onset asthma should prompt consideration of underlying conditions such as eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis (EGPA).","The presence of constitutional symptoms, peripheral neuropathy, and skin changes alongside adult-onset asthma suggests EGPA rather than primary asthma.","ANCA-positive EGPA typically presents with more vasculitic features (purpura, neuropathy) while ANCA-negative disease shows more tissue eosinophilia."],"references":["Emmi G, Bettiol A, Gelain E, Bajema IM, Berti A, Burns S, Cid MC, Cohen Tervaert JW, Cottin V, Durante E, Holle JU. Evidence-Based Guideline for the diagnosis and management of eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis. Nature Reviews Rheumatology. 2023 Jun;19(6):378-93. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41584-023-00958-w"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62210"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62210"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T13:34:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T13:35:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11399"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76718"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":